'''Enchū Suwa/Kosaka Enchū''' (諏訪 円忠/小坂 円忠) ({{ill|Einin|ja|永仁|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 ({{ill|1295|ja|1295th year|12=draft|12=draft}}) – {{ill|Jōji|ja|貞治|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 ({{ill|1364|ja|1364th year|12=draft|12=draft}})) was an official of the {{ill|Kamakura shogunate|ja|鎌倉幕府|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Muromachi shogunate|ja|Ashikaga Shogunate|12=draft|12=draft}}, and the founder of the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏#京都諏訪氏|Suwa clan=Suwa clan|lt=Kyoto Suwa clan|12=draft|12=draft}}. He is the author of the {{ill|Suwa Daimyōjin Ekotoba|ja|諏方大明神画詞|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Life ==
Born in {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|12=draft|12=draft}}, Suwa District, Enchū was the son of Suwa Moritada. According to the {{ill|Kami Clan Genealogy|ja|神氏系図|12=draft|12=draft}}, he was a branch member of the {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}} Upper Shrine family and inherited the position of {{ill|jitō|ja|地頭|12=draft|12=draft}} for {{ill|Shinomiya-shō|ja|四宮荘|12=draft|12=draft}} Funayama village in {{ill|Hanishina District|ja|埴科郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, leading to his alternate name, '''Kosaka Enchū'''. His holdings also included lands in {{ill|Etchū Province|ja|Etchū Province|12=draft|12=draft}}, Takagi Village, and the villages of Miyake-gō Jūniri and Akanoi in {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|12=draft|12=draft}}. The Suwa clan served as {{ill|gokenin|ja|被官|12=draft|12=draft}} under the {{ill|Hōjō clan|ja|北条氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, and Enchū’s uncle Suwa Tokimitsu was also an official of the Kamakura shogunate, fostering Enchū’s upbringing and service in Kamakura.
After the fall of the Hōjō clan, Enchū traveled to Kyoto and, through the mediation of {{ill|Musō Soseki|ja|夢窓疎石|12=draft|12=draft}}, entered the service of {{ill|Ashikaga Takauji|ja|足利尊氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. He rose through the ranks from {{ill|Hyōjōshū|ja|評定衆|12=draft|12=draft}} to protectorate administrator, eventually overseeing the construction of {{ill|Tenryū-ji|ja|天竜寺|12=draft|12=draft}}. He later became the administrator of {{ill|Zen temple affairs|ja|禅律方|12=draft|12=draft}}, managing Zen-related issues. Enchū also contributed to the revival of the Suwa clan, whose main line had declined after the {{ill|Revolt of Nakasendai|ja|中先代の乱|12=draft|12=draft}}, and helped establish a system where warriors across Shinano participated in the annual Suwa Upper Shrine festival.
In {{ill|Enbun|ja|延文|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 ({{ill|1356|ja|1356年|12=draft|12=draft}}), Enchū completed the {{ill|Suwa Daimyōjin Ekotoba|ja|諏方大明神画詞|12=draft|12=draft}}, which bore a postscript by Takauji. This work spread Suwa faith throughout various strata of society, including the court nobility. As part of Takauji’s initiative to establish a national network of {{ill|Ankoku-ji|ja|安国寺利生塔|1=Ankoku-ji|Ankoku-ji=Ankoku-ji|lt=Ankokuji temples|12=draft|12=draft}}, Enchū founded {{ill|Shinano Ankokuji|ja|安国寺 (茅野市)|12=draft|12=draft}} near the Suwa Upper Shrine with Musō Soseki as its founding abbot.
Enchū also inherited knowledge of {{ill|falconry|ja|鷹匠|12=draft|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Nezu clan|ja|祢津氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, a branch of the Suwa clan, as recorded in the {{ill|Kami Clan Genealogy|ja|神氏系図|12=draft|12=draft}}. This expertise was passed down among the heads of the Kyoto Suwa clan, and in {{ill|Bunmei|ja|文明|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 ({{ill|1473|ja|1473rd year|12=draft|12=draft}}), Suwa Tadakuni collaborated with the {{ill|Asukai clan|ja|飛鳥井家|12=draft|12=draft}} on annotated falconry waka poetry for {{ill|Ashikaga Yoshimasa|ja|足利義政|12=draft|12=draft}}, recorded in the {{ill|Taka Hyakushu-chū|ja|鷹百首註|12=draft|12=draft}}. Tadakuni’s son, Suwa Sadamichi, compiled a treatise on falconry titled {{ill|Taka Kikigaki Shōshō|ja|鷹聞書少々|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Enchū also excelled in waka and renga poetry, with works selected for the {{ill|Shin Chokusenshū|ja|新千載和歌集|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shin Goshūishū|ja|新後拾遺和歌集|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Tsukubashū|ja|菟玖波集|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>[https://www.ro-da.jp/shinshu-dcommons/museum_history/03OD0624101600] "Kami Clan Genealogy: Copy of Maeda Manuscript"</ref>
